What are the most important aviation sectors in Jordan, and the most pressing challenges facing them?

We are focusing on four sectors that are aviation, airspace, immigration, and the army. However, we are undertaking a project now to transform Jordan’s airspace into the Caribbean, where countries with weak air navigation systems are mergers. This means that another country assumes responsibility for navigation according to certain rules, while the two countries will have similar air, navigation, communication, and security systems, as with air traffic control. We also have the same problems as other countries in establishing immigration offices at the airports, such as moving them to a wise location. The army plays an important role in the safety and security of the airport, and similar events can happen at any country’s airport. Keeping hazards in mind, we have to work closely with all agencies, particularly the army, civil aviation, and all others with regards to how to ensure the safety and security of airports. We also need our strategic partners, who are the airlines, to survive innovations, such as Zayed Airport in Abu Dhabi, or, if I might say so, Dubai, 35 years ago, which has now grown to be the largest and most important airport in the Arab world.
